{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e8f1a2f7-064a-4bf2-80d5-9be32aeed370","content":"Setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the page tells the layout to ignore safe area insets, but there are a couple of other things that commonly cause residual padding:\n\n**1. Hide the navigation chrome:**\n\n```xml\n<!-- If using Shell -->\nShell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n\n<!-- If using NavigationPage -->\nNavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"\n```\n\n**2. On Android (.NET 10), disable automatic edge-to-edge padding:**\n\n.NET 10 enforces edge-to-edge on Android and automatically adds padding for system bars. You need to opt out:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:android=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.AndroidSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             android:Page.EdgeToEdgePaddingEdges=\"None\"\n             ...>\n```\n\n**3. On iOS, disable safe area usage:**\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n             ...>\n```\n\n**4. Ensure your Image fills the space:**\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\nThe most likely culprit for .NET 10 is #2 — the automatic edge-to-edge padding on Android that was introduced alongside the OS-enforced edge-to-edge behavior.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ee3640b4-dd2a-4cea-970c-9a81f2b3b367","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10, specifically wanting an image to fill the entire screen behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a question about .NET MAUI's safe area / edge-to-edge display APIs. Let me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to go truly edge-to-edge, you typically need to:\n\n1. Ignore the safe area insets (which `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` or similar should handle)\n\n\n2. Handle platform-specific requirements since Android and iOS have different approaches to system UI and safe areas.\n\nIn .NET 10 MAUI, Android apps are edge-to-edge by default following Android 15's requirements, but iOS requires a different approach. The issue is likely that `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` alone isn't sufficient—on iOS specifically, I need to look at whether there's a padding or margin property that's still being applied, or if there's a different MAUI property for controlling safe area behavior on that platform. the real issue might be that the Shell or NavigationPage wrapper is adding padding on top of the Page's safe area settings, so the user needs to check if they're disabling safe areas at the right level—possibly on the Shell itself rather than just the Page. the most likely issue in .NET MAUI targeting .NET 10 is:\n\n1. If using Shell navigation, the Shell itself adds navigation chrome\n2. On Android with .NET 10's edge-to-edge default, padding is automatically applied to account for system bars - you need to opt out of that padding\n3. On iOS, `UseSafeArea` needs to be set to false\n\nLet me provide a comprehensive answer. The key things to check:\n\n1. **Hide the navigation bar**: If using NavigationPage or Shell, hide the nav bar with `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` or `NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"`\n2. **On iOS**: Use `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` \n3. **On Android (.NET 10)**: The app is edge-to-edge by default, but the framework may add padding. I'm less certain about the exact property name here - it could be `EdgeToEdgePadding` or `IgnoreSafeArea` depending on the specific .NET 10 API, but the general approach is to disable the automatic safe area padding that the framework applies for system bars. The most likely issue is that the user needs to:\n1. Also hide the navigation bar (Shell or NavigationPage)\n2. On Android, handle the edge-to-edge padding that .NET 10 adds by default\n3. Potentially set properties on the specific view (Image) rather than just the page\n\nFor .NET 10 specifically, even with safe area disabled at the page level, the framework might still apply padding for system bars. The key is likely setting `Page.SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` to disable all safe area padding across platforms, though if that doesn't work, the padding could be coming from the Shell/NavigationPage itself or default layout padding that needs to be explicitly removed.","outputTokens":1942,"requestId":"0816:1BA770:3FDCA:4A0C9:69F2AB04"},"id":"ed18b4b0-a7cb-455e-ac7a-623ae5d9f3d6","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:06:49.401Z","parentId":"75a2bb83-9a11-4b5f-bd54-75b1db9b8c0e"}
